WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:22.360
Welcome to my talk.

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:26.920
So pretty early in my data science career, I was introduced to a worrying statistic when

00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:33.279
I was told that 80% of data science projects never successfully go into production.

00:00:33.279 --> 00:00:38.799
This is an unverifiable statistic, but I think you related to it or you would not have shown

00:00:38.799 --> 00:00:42.240
up for the talk.

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:46.680
This is worrying because we invest a lot of time in a data science project, a lot of your

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:51.040
personal time, a lot of company resources.

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:54.720
Looking back on six years in hindsight, the bad news is that this is probably true, if

00:00:54.720 --> 00:01:00.880
not an underestimate of how many projects fail to go to production successfully.

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:05.879
But the good news is that I think you can reliably be among the 20% whose projects do

00:01:05.879 --> 00:01:11.879
successfully go to production if you implement the steps from this talk.

00:01:11.879 --> 00:01:16.360
So we can start off with why wouldn't a data science project go to production after all

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:19.279
the expense invested in it.

00:01:19.279 --> 00:01:25.360
One of the first reasons is that many launch-ready projects die in the backlog, awaiting prioritization.

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:33.480
Second, many projects get deployed, but their potential adopters are unaware of their existence.

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:37.839
And finally, even for projects that get deployed, people are aware of them.

00:01:37.839 --> 00:01:45.680
The difficulty of using those projects can incede the incentives to use those same projects.

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:50.000
So how do you ensure that your data science project goes into production and gets widely

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
adopted?

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:57.879
I have found an enormous amount of value from a small book written 90 years ago called How

00:01:57.879 --> 00:02:01.279
to Win Friends and Influence People.

00:02:01.279 --> 00:02:06.820
This is a book that kept getting recommended over and over again for probably two decades

00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:11.360
before I finally picked it up, and I think it took me a long time to pick it up because

00:02:11.360 --> 00:02:15.199
my initial reaction to the title was, ick.

00:02:15.199 --> 00:02:19.800
It sounds like a shmarmy, manipulative way to deal with leaders and colleagues.

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:24.479
But if you, I highly encourage you to, if you actually open the book, what you'll find

00:02:24.479 --> 00:02:28.000
is that it's about empathy.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.639
It's a book about winning over colleagues and influencing leaders by listening to and

00:02:31.639 --> 00:02:34.360
designing around their needs.

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:37.600
And I think it's a really productive approach to working with people who have different

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:42.080
needs than you and who have different agendas and different goals, and they're equally valid

00:02:42.080 --> 00:02:46.360
with your own, but they are different.

00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:50.360
So step one, influence leadership.

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:55.679
This is the first step in any successful data science project launch.

00:02:55.679 --> 00:02:59.320
You need to start by identifying a problem worth solving.

00:02:59.320 --> 00:03:02.600
And for me at Intuit, this focused around A-B testing.

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:05.679
And some of you may not be as familiar with what A-B testing looks like in industry, so

00:03:05.679 --> 00:03:07.440
I'll anchor with a small example.

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:12.360
This was a race mode timer that we tested in the last tax season.

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:13.360
Very simple.

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:15.279
In recipe A, you get no timer.

00:03:15.279 --> 00:03:17.419
This is your control condition.

00:03:17.419 --> 00:03:22.360
Recipe B, you get a predicted duration of your tax filing, and you have a timer running

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:23.360
against it.

00:03:23.360 --> 00:03:25.759
And it's just a simple question.

00:03:25.759 --> 00:03:33.039
Does this feature increase the probability that you'll complete your taxes?

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:39.720
So in 2022, our A-B tests, on average, were taking 30 to 60 days to complete.

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:44.600
And in a precious traffic window like tax season, that's a lot of lost opportunity.

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:52.039
So reducing A-B test duration by 25% became among the company's top goals.

00:03:52.039 --> 00:03:57.320
So after identifying a problem worth solving, now you need to sell your solution to leadership

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:01.520
in terms that they understand and already care about.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:07.360
So these terms should not be abstract statistical terms or mathematical proofs.

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:11.360
You should, and I highly encourage you to do that for yourself, to convince yourself

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:14.199
that this is a valid and sustainable solution.

00:04:14.199 --> 00:04:17.359
But that's not going to be the pitch to leadership.

00:04:17.359 --> 00:04:22.799
The terms that they care about are often going to be time and money.

00:04:22.799 --> 00:04:26.720
So how does your solution save your customers' time, or how is it going to optimize their

00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:28.279
tax refund?

00:04:28.519 --> 00:04:31.920
Alternatively, how does this solution save our employees' time, or how is it going to

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:34.239
make money for the business?

00:04:34.239 --> 00:04:38.880
These are the kinds of terms that are going to highly motivate and get the attention of

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:43.839
your leaders to back your proposed solution.

00:04:43.839 --> 00:04:51.160
So got a relevant problem, 30 to 60 days needed for fixed sample A-B tests.

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:52.720
And I have a proposed solution.

00:04:52.720 --> 00:04:56.399
That was to increase test speed with sequential A-B testing.

00:04:56.519 --> 00:05:02.720
So fixed samples tests, these are your classic Fisher t-tests, chi-square.

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:07.399
There's a fixed sample needed before you can perform a valid analysis.

00:05:07.399 --> 00:05:12.440
Sequential A-B testing is a suite of methods, but it allows you to look at the data either

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:18.679
every day or at fixed periods without undermining the integrity of the test.

00:05:18.679 --> 00:05:20.519
It's not just peaking on a fixed sample test.

00:05:20.519 --> 00:05:24.200
This is a valid way to look at the data early.

00:05:24.799 --> 00:05:29.559
Okay, so how do you win leadership support for a solution like this?

00:05:29.559 --> 00:05:35.720
Again, by demonstrating time-money benefits, also in familiar business scenarios.

00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:40.760
You're going to want to avoid examples like dice games and marbles in a jar.

00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:44.940
Anchor it to the kind of business context that they're already familiar with.

00:05:44.940 --> 00:05:49.820
And these are the actual slides that I used to sell our senior leadership that sequential

00:05:49.820 --> 00:05:52.239
testing was a promising way forward.

00:05:52.279 --> 00:05:59.239
So what I did is I simulated thousands of A-B testing scenarios, and then I just observed

00:05:59.239 --> 00:06:03.559
the performance of fixed sample tests against the sequential testing methods that I was

00:06:03.559 --> 00:06:04.559
proposing.

00:06:04.559 --> 00:06:10.160
So in the first case, how much faster would our sequential tests end when no effect is

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:11.160
present?

00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:15.440
So we're testing A versus B, but because I wrote the simulations, I know there is absolutely

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:18.399
no real difference between these two conditions.

00:06:18.399 --> 00:06:22.640
How much faster will sequential tests end?

00:06:22.640 --> 00:06:27.079
So on my Y-axis, I have a tally of the simulated tests.

00:06:27.079 --> 00:06:32.559
On my X-axis, I have the sample size when those sequential tests ended.

00:06:32.559 --> 00:06:36.679
And then in the dotted line, I have for reference, I have the fixed sample size that would have

00:06:36.679 --> 00:06:39.279
been required under these testing conditions.

00:06:39.279 --> 00:06:41.799
So in this case, it was 31,000.

00:06:41.799 --> 00:06:44.859
How long would the sequential tests end?

00:06:44.859 --> 00:06:52.619
On average, when no effect was present, a sequential test was taking just 14,000 samples

00:06:52.619 --> 00:06:54.440
to conclude.

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:59.299
This is a 60 percent time savings over a fixed sample test.

00:06:59.299 --> 00:07:00.899
And there's a long tail.

00:07:00.899 --> 00:07:02.339
Nothing's free in life.

00:07:02.339 --> 00:07:07.500
But by the time you reach your fixed sample size, 91 percent of your tests have concluded.

00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:09.880
So I think this is a very worthwhile tradeoff.

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:12.420
This is just when no effect is present.

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:17.220
Well, another familiar business scenario, how much faster would sequential tests end

00:07:17.220 --> 00:07:22.540
if a small improvement was present, say like a 1 percent lift?

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:27.980
So same plot again, and the fixed sample test always takes the same amount of time.

00:07:27.980 --> 00:07:29.140
It's a fixed sample.

00:07:29.140 --> 00:07:33.339
Under these testing conditions, a fixed sample takes the same amount of time.

00:07:33.339 --> 00:07:38.579
But now, when the 1 percent lift is present, on average, we're taking just 18,000 samples,

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:45.339
a 40 percent savings compared to the fixed sample test.

00:07:45.339 --> 00:07:50.540
And finally, we could look at how much faster sequential tests end when a treatment is harmful.

00:07:50.540 --> 00:07:54.059
So you never want to do this, but this is also why we A-B test.

00:07:54.059 --> 00:07:57.299
We don't want to roll out features that hurt the customer.

00:07:57.299 --> 00:08:05.940
So if you roll out something and unintentionally it has a 1 percent harm, now you get enormous

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:07.940
savings.

00:08:08.299 --> 00:08:12.980
That's 5,000 samples on average, and 100 percent of the tests are ending faster than the fixed

00:08:12.980 --> 00:08:13.980
sample required.

00:08:13.980 --> 00:08:16.739
That's an 85 percent time savings.

00:08:16.739 --> 00:08:22.820
That's an 85 percent reduction in the number of customers who are exposed to an unintentionally

00:08:22.820 --> 00:08:24.380
unhelpful feature.

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:31.019
I think this slide alone may have sold leadership that this was a method worth pursuing.

00:08:31.019 --> 00:08:36.979
But again, I just want to emphasize, there's no fancy statistical terms being used.

00:08:37.020 --> 00:08:40.619
We did our homework, we did the mathematical proofs, but that's not the pitch.

00:08:40.619 --> 00:08:43.059
When you're selling it to leadership, you want to put this in terms that they already

00:08:43.059 --> 00:08:47.020
care about and understand.

00:08:47.020 --> 00:08:51.960
So for the summary on influencing leadership, you need to sell your solution by identifying

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:58.739
a problem worth solving, pitching a solution in terms that they already care about, and

00:08:58.739 --> 00:09:03.419
building trust in your data science solution through simulated data trials in very familiar

00:09:03.419 --> 00:09:08.219
business scenarios.

00:09:08.219 --> 00:09:13.260
And then this section closes with, you need to leave with a clear endorsement from leadership

00:09:13.260 --> 00:09:17.059
for adoption of your solution.

00:09:17.059 --> 00:09:19.460
And they're going to be eager to get behind it.

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:23.340
I think you actually need to be thinking ahead to part two, which is how fast can you roll

00:09:23.340 --> 00:09:30.900
out your solution once they get behind your proposal.

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:35.619
So this brings us to step two, winning over your colleagues.

00:09:35.619 --> 00:09:39.659
So leadership's endorsed your solution, and they're now asking, like, great, we want to

00:09:39.659 --> 00:09:43.059
endorse this, we want people to adopt it.

00:09:43.059 --> 00:09:46.820
You don't want this to be something that's jammed down your colleague's throat, or is

00:09:46.820 --> 00:09:49.900
just miserable for them to implement.

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:52.859
And this is where design is going to come in heavily, is where your colleagues are concerned.

00:09:52.859 --> 00:09:59.419
You want to design a user-friendly tool, and then provide adequate support for adoption.

00:10:00.419 --> 00:10:03.859
Excuse me.

00:10:03.859 --> 00:10:09.059
So I can proudly say our first sequential testing apps were unusable.

00:10:09.059 --> 00:10:13.659
But luckily, we had done lots of user testing with the analysts that went into it, and they

00:10:13.659 --> 00:10:15.419
told us this early on.

00:10:15.419 --> 00:10:20.380
They would say things like, I don't even know where to look, I don't know where to start,

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:23.940
I don't know what I should do.

00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:29.099
And so we took this feedback, we heard it, but we didn't really know how to act on it.

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:33.460
And that's where, like, the second book recommendation in this presentation comes in, which is design

00:10:33.460 --> 00:10:35.460
of everyday things.

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:41.859
Philosophically, this is very closely aligned with how to win friends and influence people.

00:10:41.859 --> 00:10:46.099
Same theme again, like, you have your needs, you have your agenda, but you need to recognize

00:10:46.099 --> 00:10:51.219
that the people you're trying to influence may have different needs, and see those validly

00:10:51.219 --> 00:10:52.940
and meet them halfway.

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:57.340
So you don't need to read the whole book, I think the first three chapters alone are

00:10:57.340 --> 00:11:02.299
enough to provide the framework for how to navigate these design challenges, and it's

00:11:02.299 --> 00:11:07.500
gonna allow you to combine your vision of how you want people to use your app, or data

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:12.219
science project, with their feedback about how they expected to use the app.

00:11:12.219 --> 00:11:16.580
And you can make a wonderful halfway meeting point.

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:21.059
And this is what it looked like for us, okay?

00:11:21.059 --> 00:11:24.260
So when you come to the app, you know, we were acting to people who were like, I don't

00:11:24.260 --> 00:11:25.260
know where to look.

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:27.380
We needed to hit them with everything all at once.

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:30.539
So now we did a scaffolded introduction to the app.

00:11:30.539 --> 00:11:33.619
First question you get asked, where are your test data?

00:11:33.619 --> 00:11:34.619
Are they in the data lake?

00:11:34.619 --> 00:11:37.619
Are they in a CSV file?

00:11:37.619 --> 00:11:42.780
Second, it's often gonna be several months between your release of an application or

00:11:42.780 --> 00:11:48.159
project, the training associated with it, and when they actually go to use it.

00:11:48.159 --> 00:11:52.739
So just expect that they'll have forgotten 95% of everything that you told them, and

00:11:52.739 --> 00:11:57.900
so we always include a hyperlink to the original training materials, where they can see a recording

00:11:57.900 --> 00:12:01.179
and a brief wiki.

00:12:01.179 --> 00:12:04.820
Good lesson from the book is when your wiki is getting really long, that's a clue you

00:12:04.820 --> 00:12:07.460
need to go back and redesign the product.

00:12:07.460 --> 00:12:13.340
But so after they've provided us with their data location, we do a quick validation that

00:12:13.340 --> 00:12:18.020
the data are in the correct structure for the app to ingest.

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:21.219
And then we ask them a few questions about their data.

00:12:21.219 --> 00:12:24.219
So for instance, what is your control name?

00:12:24.219 --> 00:12:27.640
What is the primary metric you're evaluating your A-B tests with?

00:12:27.640 --> 00:12:31.979
And what is your minimum detectable effect?

00:12:31.979 --> 00:12:35.619
After we gather this data from them, we run the analysis.

00:12:35.619 --> 00:12:40.820
And in the upper right in bold green, you get a clear call to action.

00:12:40.820 --> 00:12:43.719
So our recommendation is that you stop the experiment for revenue.

00:12:43.719 --> 00:12:49.739
Your power has exceeded 80%, which is a widely used power threshold.

00:12:49.739 --> 00:12:53.080
And in the lower right, you can see the decisions.

00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:59.380
So in this case, recipe B is offering a statistically significant improvement in revenue.

00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:06.260
And the team can now move on from their test.

00:13:06.260 --> 00:13:10.500
So summary for winning over your colleagues.

00:13:10.500 --> 00:13:14.919
You need to promote your colleagues' adoption of your solution by designing user-friendly

00:13:14.919 --> 00:13:19.179
interface and ensuring adequate support for adoption.

00:13:19.179 --> 00:13:22.179
So to do this, we use the user-friendly design.

00:13:22.179 --> 00:13:27.900
But this second step was really important, is that we chose to do team-by-team interactive

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:29.940
trainings.

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:35.000
Most data science projects I see rolled out, they may have one or two mass trainings with

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.320
300 or 500 people present.

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:42.179
That's not an environment where people are going to ask vulnerable questions or try to

00:13:42.179 --> 00:13:46.020
reconcile their needs with what you're offering them.

00:13:46.020 --> 00:13:50.039
Team-by-team interactive trainings, these are like 10 people or less.

00:13:50.039 --> 00:13:55.780
People get very comfortable asking those dumb, vulnerable questions that actually ensure

00:13:55.780 --> 00:13:58.659
that they're going to feel confident using the tool.

00:13:58.659 --> 00:14:01.340
The second key piece is that it's interactive.

00:14:01.340 --> 00:14:05.500
If you're merely talked at for an hour on how to use an application, there's very low

00:14:05.500 --> 00:14:09.260
likelihood that you're going to retain or feel confident applying any of that.

00:14:09.260 --> 00:14:12.539
We always use the show, then do rhythm.

00:14:12.539 --> 00:14:14.880
So we would demonstrate a capability of the app.

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:18.400
And then we would have them, for instance, change the primary metric and then perform

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:20.440
the same steps themselves.

00:14:20.440 --> 00:14:23.359
This makes the training a lot stickier.

00:14:23.359 --> 00:14:31.280
Finally, we offered ongoing support in a Slack channel, sequential testing support.

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:35.880
And I want to emphasize that because we took those first two steps of it was a user-friendly

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:42.719
design and we had provided adequate training, we were not overwhelmed with minutiae requests

00:14:42.719 --> 00:14:44.000
in the Slack channel.

00:14:44.119 --> 00:14:47.440
A lot of times, the questions we were getting in the Slack channel were actually really

00:14:47.440 --> 00:14:53.200
provocative or really exemplary requests that other people could benefit from seeing the

00:14:53.200 --> 00:14:54.799
conversation around.

00:14:54.799 --> 00:14:59.679
The tone in which you respond in the Slack channel is also going to set a lot of expectation

00:14:59.679 --> 00:15:04.799
around whether people are irritating you with their help requests or whether this is a collaborative

00:15:04.799 --> 00:15:06.679
effort that they're participating in.

00:15:06.679 --> 00:15:13.719
And I think, you know, if you take these three steps, it is a lot more work than just

00:15:13.719 --> 00:15:16.760
doing, you know, rapid rollout and mass training.

00:15:16.760 --> 00:15:21.840
But this is what it takes, you know, to see widespread adoption.

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:22.840
Okay.

00:15:22.840 --> 00:15:26.799
So step three, implement, track, and report.

00:15:26.799 --> 00:15:30.400
So if leadership has endorsed your solution and your colleagues feel empowered to use

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:33.979
it, you're going to get widespread adoption.

00:15:33.979 --> 00:15:38.479
You need to be thinking ahead and have a measurement plan in place beforehand for how

00:15:38.479 --> 00:15:42.820
you're going to track adoption rate and estimate the benefits of your project.

00:15:42.820 --> 00:15:47.739
So we reached 100% adoption, but now we needed to go back to leadership and tell them, well,

00:15:47.739 --> 00:15:51.700
how do we fare against this goal to reduce test duration by 25%?

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:55.640
And importantly, what was that worth?

00:15:55.640 --> 00:16:01.460
So the way that we did this was that every sequential test under the hood was computing

00:16:01.460 --> 00:16:04.059
a fixed sample power analysis.

00:16:04.059 --> 00:16:05.659
So we weren't just going to rely on simulations anymore.

00:16:05.659 --> 00:16:09.340
We would know for every single test how long it actually took and how long it would have

00:16:09.340 --> 00:16:14.340
taken if they had run the same analysis in a fixed sample test.

00:16:14.340 --> 00:16:17.760
And what we found, on average, was right in line with our simulations.

00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:23.219
We had an average savings of 63%, and you can see in the negative territory that some

00:16:23.219 --> 00:16:25.619
tests did run longer.

00:16:25.619 --> 00:16:31.700
But on average, this was an enormous time savings, well exceeding our 25% goal.

00:16:31.700 --> 00:16:38.340
But when tests end 63% faster, that means that there's more time in season for customers

00:16:38.340 --> 00:16:42.119
to enjoy the best experiences.

00:16:42.119 --> 00:16:47.500
So what we then did is we calculated the incremental revenue gain from faster rollout on every

00:16:47.500 --> 00:16:49.960
sequential test.

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:54.340
And so what you're seeing is it's obviously the sequential tests are on the Y axis.

00:16:54.340 --> 00:17:00.640
The blue section is, I should say the full length of the bar, is the revenue associated

00:17:00.640 --> 00:17:03.140
with that rollout.

00:17:03.140 --> 00:17:06.979
And if you go back to the blue section, that's how much the revenue would have been if we

00:17:06.979 --> 00:17:11.380
had done the delayed rollout on a fixed sample test.

00:17:11.380 --> 00:17:15.880
So now we could sum up the green incremental revenue gain from sequential testing across

00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:22.020
all of our tests, and we could report back that not only did we save 63% time-wise, but

00:17:22.020 --> 00:17:31.579
that this method had increased revenue by 38% relative to the methods that we replaced.

00:17:31.579 --> 00:17:38.739
So in my closing summary, you can be among that 20% of data science projects that go

00:17:38.739 --> 00:17:44.160
to production if you influence your leaders with accessible terminology, if you win over

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:50.260
your colleagues with accessible design, measure and report out regularly on your progress.

00:17:50.260 --> 00:17:54.939
And there's one other thing, and that's don't go it alone.

00:17:54.939 --> 00:17:56.619
There are no 10x engineers.

00:17:56.619 --> 00:18:01.459
There are no 10x data scientists, but there absolutely are 10x partnerships.

00:18:01.459 --> 00:18:07.020
So if you want to run 10 times as far and 10 times as fast, find a great running partner,

00:18:07.020 --> 00:18:15.380
find a great coach, and then form a great running club.

00:18:15.380 --> 00:18:16.660
Thank you all for attending today.

00:18:16.660 --> 00:18:17.660
Thank you.

00:18:17.660 --> 00:18:18.660
All right.

00:18:18.660 --> 00:18:19.660
Thank you, Joseph.

00:18:19.660 --> 00:18:31.339
So you did a really lovely job of walking us through that entire experience.

00:18:31.339 --> 00:18:37.300
If you did that again, what would you do differently?

00:18:37.300 --> 00:18:44.020
Before you launch, make fake data representing everything that you're expecting to come into

00:18:44.020 --> 00:18:45.199
your pipeline.

00:18:45.199 --> 00:18:47.800
This is for the tracking piece, that third piece.

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:52.199
And then just make sure that all of the fake data is making it perfectly into the lake,

00:18:52.199 --> 00:18:54.119
exactly as you expected.

00:18:54.119 --> 00:18:55.520
This is so much easier.

00:18:55.520 --> 00:19:02.199
I would 100% delay release by a week or two to be 100% confident that all of the tracking

00:19:02.199 --> 00:19:04.520
is exactly as I expected.

00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:06.400
As you can guess, we didn't do that.

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:12.359
And I can tell you that that one or two weeks easily cost us two to three months in trying

00:19:12.359 --> 00:19:16.000
to recover from just violated assumptions.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:19.160
Not statistical assumptions, just assumptions on how you thought the data was going to move.

00:19:19.160 --> 00:19:22.479
So yeah, run fake data through the pipelines before any release.

00:19:22.479 --> 00:19:27.880
It's like an ironclad rule now on future releases that absolutely nothing gets released until

00:19:27.880 --> 00:19:30.640
we're confident that the logging is in place.

00:19:30.640 --> 00:19:31.640
OK.

00:19:31.640 --> 00:19:32.640
Fantastic.

00:19:32.640 --> 00:19:33.640
Thank you.

00:19:33.640 --> 00:19:34.640
Let's thank all of our speakers again.

00:19:34.640 --> 00:19:34.640


